1. Caching

Cache-Control: instruction of request and responseÂ cache;
Etag: <cache_id>check if the resource was updated by comparing <cache_id>, if notâ€Šâ€”â€Šupdate the cachedÂ version;

2. HTTP/2
Pros:

Multiple HTTP connection calls (HTTP/1 supports onlyÂ 6);
A server can push an event to aÂ client;
Compress headers;
More secure

Cons:

Server push can beÂ abused;
Can be slower if LB (Load Balancer) supports HTTP/1 and serverÂ HTTP/2

3. Security

Transfer-Encodingâ€Šâ€”â€Šdefines how to encrypt body: chunked,Â gzip;
Access-Control-Allow-Origin (Cross-Origin Resource Sharingâ€Šâ€”â€ŠCORS) Defines a list of domains that can access the API of the originÂ domain;
JSONPâ€Šâ€”â€Šrun script to access cross-domain data (old browser);
X-Frame-Optionsâ€Šâ€”â€ŠPrevent clickjacking fromÂ iframe;
Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF). Attack: user has a session (logged in), attacker creates link, user clicks on the link and performs the request, attacker steals user session. Prevent: captcha, log out from visitedÂ site;
Content-Security-Policyâ€Šâ€”â€Šprevent from execution harmfulÂ code;
X-XSS-Protectionâ€Šâ€”â€ŠEnable XSS protection for oldÂ sites;
Feature-Policyâ€Šâ€”â€ŠDisable not needed Browser features;
Referrer-Policyâ€Šâ€”â€Šwhen there is a link to another website from your site, by clicking it will send the URL of origin which can contain some sensitive data (user id, session);
Don't allow the user to input any HTML innerHtmlÂ ;
Use UI frameworks, keep node_modules updated, and limit of usage 3rd party services;

Web Performance
https://medium.com/media/20dd3f56737f6d69b5613f0c9e1b8361/href
1. Critical Rendering Pathâ€Šâ€”â€Šsteps browser makes to paint the page. The stepsÂ are:

DOMâ€Šâ€”â€Šbrowser compiles the Document ObjectÂ Model;
CSSOMâ€Šâ€”â€Šbrowser compiles the CSS ObjectÂ Model;
Render Treeâ€Šâ€”â€Šbrowser combines DOM and CSSOM to render theÂ tree;
Layoutâ€Šâ€”â€Šbrowser computes the size and position of each of theÂ objects;
Paintâ€Šâ€”â€Šbrowser converts the tree into the pixels in theÂ screen;

Optimize CRP:

Optimize the order of sourcesâ€Šâ€”â€Šload critical resources as soon as possible;
Minimize the number of sourcesâ€Šâ€”â€Šreduce the number, loadÂ async;

2. Reflow â€”Browser recalculates the position and geometries of the elements after rerender.
Optimize Reflow:

reduce DOMÂ depths;
avoid long CSS selectors, minimizeÂ rules;

3. preload, preconnect, prefetch, prerender

preloadâ€Šâ€”â€Šloads high prior sources that need to be loaded faster<link rel="preload">Â ;
preconnectâ€Šâ€”â€ŠIf some resources are required to accelerate handshake, use<link rel="preconnect">to reduceÂ latency;
prefetchâ€Šâ€”â€Šloads low prior resources and cache <link rel="prefetch">;
dns-prefetchâ€”reduce latency of resolving domain names before resources get requested <link rel="dns-prefetch">;
prerenderâ€Šâ€”â€Šsimilar to prefetch + caches whole the page <link rel="prerender">Â ;

4. Rendering Performance
JS:

Move the heavy task to the webÂ worker;
Use requestAnimatinFrame instead of setTimeoutto perform animation;

Style:

reduce the complexity of selectors;
Reduce the number of elements on which style calculation must beÂ applied;

Layout: (how an element is positioned andÂ sized)

Avoid layoutÂ changes;
Use flexbox;
Use css-grid;

Paint: (draw pixels: color, shadows; layout changes triggerÂ repaint)

Use will-change to optimize layoutÂ repaint;

5. Workers

Service Workerâ€Šâ€”â€Šinterceptor to build an offlineÂ app;
Web Workerâ€Šâ€”â€Šperform heavy tasks on background;

6. Image optimization
Format:

if animationâ€Šâ€”â€Šuse <video>instead gif
if high details and resolutionâ€Šâ€”â€ŠPNG
if geometry shapesâ€Šâ€”â€ŠSVG
if text logoâ€Šâ€”â€Šuse fontÂ text
