Javascript
https://medium.com/media/53c433cc54b5b6de2b774b317a463275/href
1. this

this is a reference to the object where a function isÂ called;
default this context isÂ window;
context which function will get from the place itÂ called;
arrow function -> takes context which function isÂ defined;
this loses context when we call one function inside anotherÂ function

function Foo() {
    console.log(this); 
}Foo(); // at this line the context is 'window'
// output: 'window'
var foo1 = new Foo(); // at this line the context binds to 'foo1'
// output: 'Foo {}'

Explicitly assign the context of thisÂ : foo1.apply(context, arrayOfArgs), foo1.call(context, arg1, arg2,Â â€¦), var foo2 = foo1.bind(context, arg1, arg2,Â â€¦)â€” returns an instance of function with givenÂ context;

2. Closureâ€Šâ€”â€Šfunctions ability to remember and access scope even if was called from another scope (function return function/block scope in blockÂ scope)
function a(arg1) { // arg1 scoped
    var arg2 = 0; // arg2 scoped
    return function b(){
        ++arg2;
        return arg1 + arg2;
    }
}
var foo = a(2);
foo(); // 2
foo(); // 3
var foo2 = a(4);
foo(); // 4
foo(); // 5
3. Inheritance

To inherit obj1 from obj2Â , you can link an object to another object var obj1 = Object.create(obj2);
JS uses prototype inheritance. Each object has a __proto__ link. If we access any property of an object, the JS engine first checks if the object has it, if notâ€Šâ€”â€Šchecks the prototype, and goes through __proto__ chain to find the property name, and then throws undefined if didnâ€™tÂ find;

4. Asynchronous Javascript

Event loop: In JS there are 3 types of memory: stack used for functions call, heap for each of the objects, queueâ€Šâ€”â€ŠsetTimeout. JS engine executes the function stack first. If the stack is empty, it pops the event from queue. If the event queue has another function call, it pushes it to stack and executes it again until it is empty. This is called eventÂ loop;
JS uses callback, promise, async-await to implement asynchronous patterns. You can read more about async JS and event loop in thisÂ article:

ğŸ”¥ The Evolution of Asynchronous Patterns in JavaScript
5. Hoisting

function definition moves to the top of block scope during JS compilation, then goes varÂ ;
let and const are hoisted too but in the temporary deadÂ zone;

// Code example              // After hoisting 
1. console.log('hoisting');  1. function foo(){
2. var a;                    2.    return null;
3. function foo(){           3. }
4.    return null;           4. var a;
5. }                         5. console.log('hoisting');
6. a = 5;                    6. a = 5;
6. Curryingâ€Šâ€”â€Šnested functions:
function calcABC(a){
    return function(b){
        return function(c){
            return a+b+c;
        }
    }
}
console.log(calcABC(1)(2)(3));
// 6
7. Higher-order functions

map, reduce, filter,Â find
You can chain higher-order function into composition

[1,2,3,4,5].map((num) => ({age: num})).filter((el) => el.age < 4);
// [{age: 1}, {age: 2}, {age: 3}]
Design patterns
https://medium.com/media/04a5e73ceb2460740f68853565b5d4d2/href
1. Mixinâ€Šâ€”â€Šextend the functionality of an object with the list ofÂ methods;
// Option 1
class Person{}
let Mixin = {foo(){}};
Object.assign(Person.prototype, Mixin);
let person = new Person();
person.foo();
// Option 2
let Mixin1 = {foo1(){}};
let Mixin2  = {__proto__: Mixin1, foo2(){}};
2. Factoryâ€Šâ€”â€Ša class that can create one or many different objects (useful if you want to generate different mock data in UnitÂ Tests);
personFactory.one({name: 'John'}); -> Person{name: 'John', age: 5}
personFactory.many(); -> [Person{name: 'Bill', age: 7}, Person{name: 'Anna', age: 3}]
3. Singletonâ€Šâ€”â€Šclass which you can call method directly, without creating anÂ object;
let mySingleton = (function() {
    let instance = null;
    function init(){
        return {
           //list all the methods
           method(){}
        }
    }
    if(instance == null){
        instance = init();
    }
    return instance;
})();
mySingleton.method();
4. Facadeâ€Šâ€”â€Šabstract more complex logic and wrap it in class. For example, service that stays between component and APIÂ layer:
ui component - Facade service (complex state object) - API layer (Redux);
5. MVC, MVVMâ€Šâ€”â€ŠModel View Controller and Model View ViewModel.
React isÂ MVC

stateâ€Šâ€”â€ŠModel;
JSXâ€Šâ€”â€ŠView;
actions (violateâ€Šâ€”â€Šcan be mixed with view)â€Šâ€”â€ŠControllerÂ ;

Angular isÂ MVVM

componentâ€Šâ€”â€ŠModelView
templateâ€Šâ€”â€ŠView (violateâ€Šâ€”â€Šnot reusable)
propertiesâ€Šâ€”â€ŠModel

6. Server vs Client-Side Rendering
SSRâ€Šâ€”â€ŠUse SSR if a site is stable, static, SEO focused, can pay for additional servers;
pros

Faster page load (viewable, but not interactable);
Better for search engines (faster indexing);
Better with sites that have a lot of static contentÂ (blogs);

cons

More server requests;
Slower render to interact;
Full pageÂ reloads;

CSRâ€Šâ€”â€ŠUse CSR if site under development, dynamic;
pros

Faster render after initialÂ load;
Best for webÂ app;

cons

The initial load can require moreÂ time

